# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemical-industry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:chemical-industry/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:chemical-industry/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Abraham Pineo Gesner was born on May 2, 1797, at Chipmans Corner, Cornwallis Township, just north of Kentville, Nova Scotia.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] He was one of 12 children raised by Henry Gesner and Sarah Pineo.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] His father was a Loyalist, who emigrated to Nova Scotia after the American Revolution.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner was noted to be a great reader and a diligent student.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In his early twenties, Gesner began a venture selling horses to plantations in the Caribbean and the United States, but this enterprise failed after he lost most of his horses in two shipwrecks.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Financially drained, Gesner returned to the family farm and married Harriet Webster, daughter of prominent Kentville doctor Isaac Webster in 1824.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Reportedly, Webster offered to take care of Gesner's debts if he would study medicine and secure a steady income for his family.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1825, Gesner travelled to London to study medicine at St Bartholomew's Hospital under Sir Astley Paston Cooper, and surgery at Guy's Hospital under John Abernethy.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While primarily a medical student, Gesner developed an interest in the earth sciences and took lectures in mineralogy and geology.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner also established a lifelong relationship with Charles Lyell.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner qualified as a doctor of medicine and settled in Parrsboro, Nova Scotia in 1827 as a travelling physician.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner also continued to pursue his passion for geology, reading the writings of notable geologists and developing a habit of picking up mineral specimens that caught his attention while making his rounds on horseback.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1836, Gesner published his first book, *Remarks on the Geology and Mineralogy of Nova Scotia.* The book expanded on an earlier geological study by Charles T.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Jackson and displayed Gesner's ability to express complicated concepts in simple language.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Following the publication of *Remarks on the Geology and Mineralogy of Nova Scotia,* Gesner focused his efforts on studying geology and the sciences connected to it.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1838, the government of New Brunswick appointed Gesner as Provincial Geologist, and he moved to Saint John to conduct a geological survey of the province.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] For five years, Gesner spent his summers on geological fieldwork and his winters classifying specimens and writing reports.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Although Gesner's geological studies were of high quality by the standards of the 1840s, he had no experience in mining and failed to make a realistic appraisal of the province's mineral reserves.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Following the publication of Gesner's geological surveys, local entrepreneurs opened coal and iron mines in Queens County and were quickly disappointed by the extent and quality of the ore.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Unhappy investors questioned the validity of Gesner's surveys and the provincial government terminated his employment in 1843.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] During the first summer of his geological surveys, Gesner found a bituminous substance on the Petitcodiac River in Albert County, which he named albertite to differentiate it from coal or asphalt.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While in Saint John, Gesner amassed an extensive collection of minerals and wildlife specimens, which he assembled into a museum in 1842.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner's museum was one of its first of its kind in British North America and had 2173 items in its catalogue.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The museum was a financial failure, and when Gesner left New Brunswick, the Saint John Mechanics’ Institute acquired the objects.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1890, the Natural History Society of New Brunswick took over the collection, which is today a part of the New Brunswick Museum.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Following the termination of his geological appointment in 1843, Gesner returned to his family homestead at Cornwallis, Nova Scotia, in order to be with his father who was then 87 years old.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While working on the family farm, Gesner also continued to practice medicine, write books, give public lectures and conduct experiments.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] He published notes for emigrants to New Brunswick, outlined the industrial resources of Nova Scotia, and built an electrical motor driven by a voltaic battery.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1846, the government of Nova Scotia appointed Gesner Commissioner of Indian Affairs, and the following year he submitted a report on the living conditions of the Miꞌkmaq population.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While visiting Mi'kmaq habitations across the province for his report, Gesner was known to donate his own money to assist impoverished families.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1842, looking for coal, Gesner travelled to Quebec, where he discovered the first of the great fossil deposits of the future Miguasha National Park.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] However, little notice was taken of his report until the fossils were rediscovered in 1879.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner likely began experimenting with hydrocarbons in the 1840s.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Utilizing a sample of bitumen from Trinidad's Pitch Lake that he collected while shipping horses across the Atlantic, Gesner developed a method of extracting oils and gas from bituminous substances.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner found that the first product was not satisfactory as it had an offensive odour, the raw material was expensive to obtain, and his experiments suggested that one ton of Trinidad bitumen would produce only 42 gallons of oil.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Switching his experiments from Trinidad's bitumen to albertite, Gesner found that the burning oil extracted from the substance produced a brighter and cleaner flame compared to lamps using whale oil or coal oil.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While undertaking a series of public lectures in Charlottetown, Gesner reportedly gave the first public demonstration of the preparation and use of the new lamp fuel in August 1846.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner first called his product "keroselain" from two Greek words, κηρός (wax) and λάδι (oil), but later contracted the name to kerosene.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Shortly after Gesner's father died on October 13, 1850, he moved his family to Sackville, a small town near Halifax, and in 1852 to Halifax.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In Halifax, Gesner made the acquaintance of Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The pair planned to set up a company that would illuminate Halifax by using albertite from Albert County, New Brunswick, and bitumen from Trinidad's pitch lake.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] However, Cochrane's terms of service expired in April 1851, and he returned to England before the pair could bring the project to fruition.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner attempted to continue the project on his own, but Halifax's city council awarded the gas license to a rival group, the Halifax Gas Company.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Moreover, although Gesner attempted to receive a lease to mine bitumen in Albert County, another entrepreneur, William Cairns, had already purchased the rights to mine coal in the area.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] After Cairns had Gesner's men forcibly expelled from the site of the bitumen deposit, Gesner brought suit against Cairns for trespassing.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The trial centered on whether the albertite deposit was coal or asphalt.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The jury, told by the judge that Cairn's license to mine coal included "other mines and minerals," ultimately sided against Gesner, resulting in albertite's misidentification as "Albert Coal" for the next 30 years.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In early 1853, following the outcome of the trial, Gesner and his family moved to New York City, where he had earlier exhibited his kerosene and amassed significant publicity.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] After arriving in New York, Gesner focused on finding financial backing for his kerosene venture.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In March 1853, Gesner partnered with shipbroker Horatio Eagle, who issued an eight-page circular entitled, *Project for the Formation of a Company to Work the Combined Patent Rights of Dr.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Abraham Gesner, Nova Scotia, and the Right Hon. the Earl of Dundonald of Middlesex, England.* The pamphlet offered for sale $100,000 in shares of a new company called the Asphalt Mining and Kerosene Company, later renamed the North American Kerosene Company.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In the patents, Gesner described three distinct types of kerosene, which he labelled kerosenes A, B and C.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Kerosene A was the most volatile fraction, known today as gasoline.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Kerosene B was slightly less volatile and was intended mainly for mixing with the other grades.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Under Gesner's guidance, the North American Kerosene Company began constructing a coal oil refinery on a seven-acre tract at Newtown Creek, Long Island, the first of its kind in North America.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] By 1856, the firm was selling kerosene for use as lamp fuel.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] According to an article in the *New York Commercial Advertiser* in August 1859, the plant cost $1.25 million to build, employed 200 men, used 30,000 tons of coal per year, and exported 5,000 gallons of kerosene per day.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Modern engineers have praised Gesner's efficient design of the factory, differing very little from manufactories built as late as 1914.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] While the enterprise had not made Gesner extremely wealthy, he lived comfortably in Brooklyn, New York, where he was a prominent figure in the local church and community.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] By the late 1850s, the North American Kerosene Company began to face increased competition as various coal oil competitors entered the scene.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In response to the increased competition, the North American Kerosene Company published a pamphlet on March 28, 1859, that advised customers that kerosene is their registered trademark and that oils made by others can not use the name.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] One prominent rival manufacturer, Samuel Downer of Boston, Massachusetts, made an agreement in early 1859 to license the name and Gesner's refinement process.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] When James Young, a Scottish chemist, who had independently developed a process of distilling a petroleum fuel into a product he named "paraffin oil," became aware of the North American Kerosene Company's claims, he filed for patent infringement and won.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Although Young only began his distillation experiments in 1848, two years after Gesner's first public demonstration of Kerosene, he was first to file an American patent for his process in 1852.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Thereafter, the North American Kerosene Company had to pay royalties to Young.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Following the discovery of oil in Enniskillen Township and Pennsylvania, the North American Kerosene Company began using petroleum to produce kerosene instead of coal at about one third the cost.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Sometime after the trial, the company replaced Gesner with Luther Atwood as chief chemist.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The Newton Creek plant eventually passed into the hands of Charles Pratt and Company, a subsidiary of Standard Oil, and continued to operate until May 1951.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1952, a junk dealer bought the refinery and sold the equipment for scrap.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner married Harriet Webster, daughter of prominent Kentville doctor Isaac Webster in 1824.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Together, they had seven sons and three daughters, but three children died in infancy.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Three of his sons, Brower (1834–1873), John Frederick (1839–1899), and George Weltden (1829–1904), pursued careers in geology and chemistry.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] For a time, Gesner remained in New York, practising medicine and continuing his research into hydrocarbons.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1861, Gesner published *A Practical Treatise on Coal, Petroleum and Other Distilled Oils*, which was extremely influential in the future development of the petroleum industry and remarkable for the accuracy of his predictions on the future course the refining business would take.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner was humble about his contribution to the development of the petroleum industry, writing in *A Practical Treatise on Coal* that "The progress of discovery in this case, as in others, has been slow and gradual.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] After the publication of *A Practical Treatise on Coal,* Gesner became a distillation consultant, visiting the oil fields in Enniskillen Township sometime around 1860.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner might have helped James Miller Williams in the development of his petroleum refinery in Hamilton in 1861.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1863, Gesner returned to Halifax, Nova Scotia, where he was offered the chair of Natural History at Dalhousie University, but he died on April 29, 1864, before he could take up the position.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Gesner was buried in an unmarked grave at Halifax's Camp Hill Cemetery.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 1933, Imperial Oil Ltd., then a Standard Oil subsidiary, erected a memorial at Gesner's grave in Camp Hill Cemetery to pay tribute to his contribution to the petroleum industry.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The monument reads "His treatise on the geology and mineralogy of Nova Scotia, 1836, was one of the earliest works dealing with those subjects in this province and about 1852 he was the American inventor of the process of kerosene oil.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 2007, Gesner was inducted into the Canadian Petroleum Hall of Fame for his contributions to the petroleum industry and in 2013 he was added to the Nova Scotia Institute for Science's Hall of Fame.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 2016, Gesner was posthumously inducted to the Order of New Brunswick by the province of his longtime residence.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Several streets are named in his honour.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] The City of Halifax renamed a street at the west end of Fairview between Melrose and Adelaide in honour of Gesner.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Formerly a part of Dunbrack Street, the construction of the Dunbrack Street/North West Arm Drive connector during the 1980s prompted the renaming of this segment.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In Ottawa, there is a street named for Gesner in the west part of Ottawa's Katimavik-Hazeldean neighbourhood, where the residential streets are named for Canadian inventors.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Whether by plan or by coincidence, it dead-ends at an Esso (Imperial Oil) gas station.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] Starting in 1998, the Fundy Geological Museum in Parrsboro Nova Scotia, a former residence of Gesner, has awarded an "Abraham Gesner Work Scholarship" to a local student who shows keen interest in the sciences.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 2000, he was honoured by the placement of his image on a postage stamp by Canada Post.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] His birthplace at Chipmans Corner, Nova Scotia was marked by a National Historic Site monument in 1954.
[src:chemical-industry/abraham-pineo-gesner] In 2019, a large sculptural monument by artist Ruth Abernethy honouring Gesner's work was added to the Chipman Corner birthplace commemoration site.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:chemical-industry/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] An **accounting network** or **accounting association** is a professional services network whose principal purpose is to provide members resources to assist the clients around the world and hence reduce the uncertainty by bringing together a greater number of resources to work on a problem.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The networks and associations operate independently of the independent members.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The largest accounting networks are known as the Big Four.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The **Big Four** are the four largest professional services networks in the world: Deloitte, EY, KPMG, and PwC.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The four are grouped because of their large sizes relative to their competitors, both in terms of revenue and workforce headcount; they are likewise considered comparable in their ability to provide consistent and reliable professional services to their clients.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Colloquially, their networks are considered *of parity* to those seeking careers in the services offered by these firms because of the frequency with which they engage with *Fortune* 500 companies.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The Big Four offer audit, assurance, taxation, management consulting, valuation, market research, actuarial, corporate finance, and legal services to their clients.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] A significant majority of the audits of public companies, as well as many audits of private companies, are conducted by these four networks.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Until the late 20th century, the market for these professional services was dominated by *eight* firms, which were accordingly nicknamed the *Big Eight*.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The Big Eight consisted of Arthur Andersen, Arthur Young, Coopers & Lybrand, Deloitte Haskins and Sells, Ernst & Whinney, Peat Marwick Mitchell, Price Waterhouse, and Touche Ross.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The Big Eight gradually evolved into the Big Four due to mergers between some of these firms, and culminated in the 2002 collapse of Arthur Andersen, leaving four networks dominating the market at the turn of the 21st century.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] In the United Kingdom in 2011, it was reported that the Big Four account for the audits of 99% of the companies in the FTSE 100 Index, and 96% of the companies in the FTSE 250 Index, an index of the leading mid-cap listing companies.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] This high level of industry concentration has caused concern among critics, and is the chief reason some notable people of business have expressed the desire for government bodies such as the UK's Competition & Markets Authority (CMA) to consider breaking up the Big Four.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] For over 70 years, the SEC has continually sought for greater coordination and consistent quality in audits everywhere in the world.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Networks were the logical model to address these requirements.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] They expanded outside of the United States since financial results had to be audited wherever a company conducted business.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] In the US, the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board's (PCAOB) regulations provide for inspection of non-United States firms.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Without a network with common standards and internal means of communications, conducting the required audits would not be possible.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] There were other profession-based factors which favored the growth of accounting networks.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] As a result of competition for the audit work, consolidation was inevitable.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] These include the fact that a network can establish a brand.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] A brand establishes the credibility of the network and allows the individual members to charge more.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Creating a brand is very difficult when all of the members of a network are providing essentially the same services.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Being a network member establishes that the firm is part of a large group.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Additionally, the larger the firm, the more likely it will be invited to render auditing engagements.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] A large organized network allows for spreading the costs to price competitively.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Ultimately, size is the only real means of differentiation that is readily available on accounting firms to assure clients that they can do international work.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Networks also reflect the clients’ needs for seamless worldwide services because they are more efficient and cost-effective.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] From the perspective of the accounting firm, a global regulated organization with consistently applied standards significantly reduced the risk.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] However, increasing the size of the networks can enhance legal liability risks and quality control issues that have not been resolved.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] With these factors in play, some networks continued to grow; others remained in a stasis position.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Individual members of networks began to offer other services related to accounting.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] These services included forensic accounting, business appraisals, employee benefits planning, strategic planning, and almost anything associated with financial parts of the client’s business.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The network’s structure easily accommodated these services and their geographical expansion.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] As the Big Eight consolidated to become Big Six, the Big Five and then the Big Four, new networks naturally developed to emulate them.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] BDO and Grant Thornton were the earliest followers.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Networks were then developed to serve mid-market companies and private businesses.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] New networks also sprang up as an extension of a single accounting firm in the same way the Big Eight were formed.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] New structures were created to further extend the networks.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The largest accounting networks adopted trade names that each member used.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The names of the original firms that became part of the networks were lost and replaced with trade names.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The perception was created that these networks were more than networks, but single entities rather than completely independent firms.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The result was that the Big Eight concept was established which separated the eight firms from all other accounting firms.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Another factor in the development of networks in accounting was the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA)’s prohibition of advertising.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] While the largest firms indirectly advertised their services, the small firms complied with the rules and believed advertising to be unprofessional.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Additionally, midsize firms were de facto restricted from advertising simply because of limited budgets.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] They could not create a brand that was able to compete with the one established by the Big Eight.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The advertising restriction was lifted in the 1970s by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] In the 1990s, the large accounting firms reached another ceiling in the services they made available to their clients.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Having reached their natural limit on growth with more than 90% of auditing for public companies, the Big 6 branched out to become multidisciplinary in legal, technology, and employment services.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Since the essential infrastructure was in place, it was thought to be relatively simple to incorporate other services into the existing network.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] As a network, it was natural to create independent entities in these other professions which themselves could be part of the network.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The method and structures varied from firm to firm.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] When the Big 6 began its expansion to the legal profession, it was met with fierce opposition from law firms and bar associations.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Commissions, panels and committees were established by legal and accounting firms to argue their positions.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] For more than five years the debate escalated.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] This movement ended abruptly with the fall of Arthur Andersen as a result of its association with Enron.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Sarbanes–Oxley followed, which effectively ended this trend.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Some international associations of independent firms, such as Alliott Group, now include law firms within the membership.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Accounting networks are adapting their operating models to address vicarious liability risks and clarify their legal structures.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Historically, many global accounting networks marketed themselves as unified entities; however, recent legal rulings have prompted these firms to distinguish between the global brand and the independent, locally incorporated member firms that actually deliver service.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Although accounting networks have been unsuccessful in several legal disputes, specific factual circumstances or procedural elements have mitigated their ultimate financial or legal liability.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The vicarious liability issues carry over into operations.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Regulations in the EU have been imposed that require the “networks” to define whether they are "associations" of independent firm or are more integrated networks operationally and financially.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Additional standards have been passed by the International Federation of Accountants, an independent organization representing the accounting industry, on distinguishing networks from associations.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The objectives of each are to provide the clients a level of understanding about the degree of integration with each other.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Examples of international associations of accounting firms include Alliott Group, GGI Global Alliance and Leading Edge Alliance.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Self-definition as a network or associations may determine if there is a conflict of interest.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] If the group is perceived as a network, it may be foreclosed from representation of clients because they cannot represent a competitor.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Association members would not be foreclosed from representation because the firms are perceived as independent by clients.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Accounting scandals have again focused on the fact that the Big Four has a near monopoly on audits of public companies.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] Networks are demanding regulations on auditing to require that auditors rotate and include the smaller networks in this rotation.
[src:chemical-industry/accounting-network] The demands also request that mid-market firms be able to participate to break up the monopoly of the Big Four.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:chemical-industry/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:chemical-industry/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:chemical-industry/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:chemical-industry/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The **chemical industry** comprises the companies and other organizations that develop and produce industrial, specialty and other chemicals.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Central to the modern world economy, the chemical industry converts raw materials (oil, natural gas, air, water, metals, and minerals) into commodity chemicals for industrial and consumer products.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] It includes industries for petrochemicals such as polymers for plastics and synthetic fibers; inorganic chemicals such as acids and alkalis; agricultural chemicals such as fertilizers, pesticides and herbicides; and other categories such as industrial gases, speciality chemicals and pharmaceuticals.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Various professionals are involved in the chemical industry including chemical engineers, chemists and lab technicians.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Although chemicals were made and used throughout history, the birth of the heavy chemical industry (production of chemicals in large quantities for a variety of uses) coincided with the beginnings of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] One of the first chemicals to be produced in large amounts through industrial processes was sulfuric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In 1736 pharmacist Joshua Ward developed a process for its production that involved heating sulfur with saltpeter, allowing the sulfur to oxidize and combine with water.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] It was the first practical production of sulphuric acid on a large scale.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] John Roebuck and Samuel Garbett were the first to establish a large-scale factory in Prestonpans, Scotland, in 1749, which used leaden condensing chambers for the manufacture of sulfuric acid.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In the early 18th century, cloth was bleached by treating it with stale urine or sour milk and exposing it to sunlight for long periods of time, which created a severe bottleneck in production.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Sulfuric acid began to be used as a more efficient agent as well as lime by the middle of the century, but it was the discovery of bleaching powder by Charles Tennant that spurred the creation of the first great chemical industrial enterprise.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] His powder was made by reacting chlorine with dry slaked lime and proved to be a cheap and successful product.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] He opened the St Rollox Chemical Works, north of Glasgow, and production went from just 52 tons in 1799 to almost 10,000 tons just five years later.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Soda ash was used since ancient times in the production of glass, textile, soap, and paper, and the source of the potash had traditionally been wood ashes in Western Europe.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] By the 18th century, this source was becoming uneconomical due to deforestation, and the French Academy of Sciences offered a prize of 2400 livres for a method to produce alkali from sea salt (sodium chloride).
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The Leblanc process was patented in 1791 by Nicolas Leblanc who then built a Leblanc plant at Saint-Denis.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] He was denied his prize money because of the French Revolution.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In Britain, the Leblanc process became popular.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] William Losh built the first soda works in Britain at the Losh, Wilson and Bell works on the River Tyne in 1816, but it remained on a small scale due to large tariffs on salt production until 1824.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] When these tariffs were repealed, the British soda industry was able to rapidly expand.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] James Muspratt's chemical works in Liverpool and Charles Tennant's complex near Glasgow became the largest chemical production centres anywhere.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] By the 1870s, the British soda output of 200,000 tons annually exceeded that of all other nations in the world combined.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] These huge factories began to produce a greater diversity of chemicals as the Industrial Revolution matured.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Originally, large quantities of alkaline waste were vented into the environment from the production of soda, provoking one of the first pieces of environmental legislation to be passed in 1863.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] This provided for close inspection of the factories and imposed heavy fines on those exceeding the limits on pollution.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Methods were devised to make useful byproducts from the alkali.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The Solvay process was developed by the Belgian industrial chemist Ernest Solvay in 1861.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In 1864, Solvay and his brother Alfred constructed a plant in Charleroi Belgium.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In 1874, they expanded into a larger plant in Nancy, France.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The new process proved more economical and less polluting than the Leblanc method, and its use spread.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] In the same year, Ludwig Mond visited Solvay to acquire the rights to use his process, and he and John Brunner formed Brunner, Mond & Co., and built a Solvay plant at Winnington, England.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Mond was instrumental in making the Solvay process a commercial success.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] He made several refinements between 1873 and 1880 that removed byproducts that could inhibit the production of sodium carbonate in the process.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The manufacture of chemical products from fossil fuels began at scale in the early 19th century.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The coal tar and ammoniacal liquor residues of coal gas manufacture for gas lighting began to be processed in 1822 at the Bonnington Chemical Works in Edinburgh to make naphtha, pitch oil (later called creosote), pitch, lampblack (carbon black) and sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride).
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Ammonium sulphate fertiliser, asphalt road surfacing, coke oil and coke were later added to the product line.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] The late 19th century saw an explosion in both the quantity of production and the variety of chemicals that were manufactured.
[src:chemical-industry/chemical-industry] Large chemical industries arose in Germany and later in the United States.
